{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567450"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:01:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:01:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19014"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19014","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19014"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.26,0.55,0.02,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11748"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116445"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11748","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11748"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19014"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98444"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"4256"},{"type":"tags","id":"4272"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27648"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31217"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35185"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37156"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46688"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49887"},{"type":"contributions","id":"50045"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116445","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116445"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department after spilling hot oil on her legs 30 minutes ago. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She does not smoke or drink alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed with pain. Her pulse rate is 104/min, blood pressure 110/68 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. She weighs 55 kg. There are deep partial thickness burns to both legs, extending posteriorly, as shown (Image 1, 2). Cool running water has been applied and she has received appropriate analgesia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be most appropriate initial fluid regimen?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["1100 ml in the first 6 hours","1100 ml in the first 8 hours","2200 ml in the first 8 hours","2200 ml in the first 16 hours","4400 ml in the first 8 hours"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has sustained significant burns requiring formal fluid resuscitation. Applying the \u0027rule of nines,\u0027 this patient has a total body surface area (TBSA) burn of about 20% and application of the Parkland formula would be appropriate. The Parkland formula is commonly used to estimate fluid requirements in the first 24 hours after a burn injury. The formula calculates total fluid requirements as 4 mL \u00d7 %TBSA \u00d7 weight in kg, with half given in the first 8 hours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E2200 mL\u003C/strong\u003E in the first 8 hours is correct. Using the Parkland formula for this 55 kg patient with 20% TBSA burns: 4 \u00d7 20 \u00d7 55 = 4400 mL total for 24 hours. Half of this (2200 mL) should be given in the first 8 hours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E1100 mL in the first 6 or 8 hours\u003C/strong\u003E would also be inadequate for initial resuscitation given the extent of burns. 1100 mL represents only one-quarter of the calculated 24-hour requirement, which would be insufficient to prevent burn shock in this patient with significant burns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E2200 mL in the first 16 hours\u003C/strong\u003E would deliver the fluid too slowly. The first 8 hours after a burn are critical for preventing burn shock and require more aggressive fluid replacement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E4400 mL\u003C/strong\u003E in the first 8 hours would be excessive and could lead to fluid overload. This volume represents the entire 24-hour requirement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile formulae provide useful initial guidance, ongoing fluid therapy should be titrated to clinical response, particularly maintaining adequate urine output (0.5-1.0 mL/kg/hour) and avoiding signs of fluid overload.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Parkland formula (4 mL x %TBSA x weight in kg) estimates 24-hour fluid requirements in burns, with half given in the first 8 hours.","Clinical signs including urine output and vital signs should guide ongoing fluid therapy rather than strictly adhering to formula calculations.","Burns \u003E15% TBSA in adults require formal fluid resuscitation to prevent burn shock."],"references":["Gilbert P, Usua G, Martin N, et al. Fluid resuscitation management in patients with burns: update. Br J Anaesth. 2016; 117:284-96."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98444"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19014"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21480"},{"type":"media","id":"21481"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21480"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/iPEBiPXML6v1G5juyhwd7DWXcOCqgK.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/iPEBiPXML6v1G5juyhwd7DWXcOCqgK.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":283}},{"type":"media","id":"21481","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21481"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/